#: ../../user/troubleshooting/disk-troubleshooting.rst:7
#: d2535a5a5be24d6aa5341a26a0753f95
msgid "\"Out of disk space\" error"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/troubleshooting/disk-troubleshooting.rst:10
#: 8dd1266303f04eb6997b9c5d9dc29461
msgid ""
"If the disk is completely full, you will get an ``Out of disk space`` "
"error that may crash your system because Dom0 does not have enough disk "
"space to work. So it’s good practice to regularly check disk space usage."
" Running the ``df -h`` command in dom0 terminal will show some "
"information, but not include all the relevant details. The Qubes user "
"interface provides a disk space widget. If you are unable to access the "
"interface, the command line version is running ``sudo lvs | head`` and "
"looking at top entry for LVM pool. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/troubleshooting/disk-troubleshooting.rst:21
#: 2e4c64878b2748b999810725bfffbb21
#, python-format
msgid ""
"If you run ``df -h``, it only shows the information in the ``root`` line "
"(which is already included in the ``pool00`` line). As you can see, the "
"``sudo lvs | head`` command includes additional important columns "
"``Data%`` and ``Meta%``, shown in the above example to have the values "
"89% and 69% respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/troubleshooting/disk-troubleshooting.rst:23
#: 3a47aaf53d6847529983e9cf40ca6647
msgid ""
"If your system is able to boot, but cannot load a desktop environment, it"
" is possible to login to dom0 terminal with Alt + Ctrl + F2."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/troubleshooting/disk-troubleshooting.rst:25
#: 780549c72ae44b26bd69291e92926fe4
msgid ""
"If this does not work, check the size of ``/var/lib/qubes/qubes.xml``. If"
" it is zero, you’ll need to use one of the file backup (stored in "
"``/var/lib/qubes/backup``), hopefully you have the current data there. "
"Find the most recent one and place in ``/var/lib/qubes/qubes.xml`` "
"instead of the empty file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/troubleshooting/disk-troubleshooting.rst:27
#: fda097fe186e4c508189ca597631aa63
msgid ""
"In any case you’ll need some disk space to start the VM. Check ``df -h`` "
"output if you have some. If not, here are some hints how to free some "
"disk space:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/troubleshooting/disk-troubleshooting.rst:29
#: 16ae3ee7885a44adbd0b23673b39b9fe
msgid "Clean yum cache."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/troubleshooting/disk-troubleshooting.rst:37
#: 8eff3a4ffa0b4a8490c7fe4ae7257d70
msgid ""
"Delete ``.img`` files of a less important VM, which can be found in "
"``/var/lib/qubes/appvms/``. Then, when the system is working again, clean"
" up the rest."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/troubleshooting/disk-troubleshooting.rst:44
#: b4e3032727e9465e8dbefd404d7e034a
msgid ""
"With this method, you lose the data of one VM, but it’ll work more "
"reliably."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/troubleshooting/disk-troubleshooting.rst:46
#: 5b05a85cd28040eea4b6eca9f1bda276
msgid "Decrease the filesystem safety margin (5% by default)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/troubleshooting/disk-troubleshooting.rst:54
#: 5391a68d2905436e9d66864327358d9d
msgid ""
"Remove some unneeded files in dom0 home (if you have any, most likely "
"not). Also look for unneeded files in ``/var/log`` in dom0, and "
"``/var/log/qubes``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/troubleshooting/disk-troubleshooting.rst:58
#: 98ce14c537ee4cccbd4035416d085ec6
msgid ""
"The above steps applies to old VM disks format. These steps may work on "
"Qubes 4.0, but are not default anymore. By default, Qubes 4.0 now uses "
"LVM. The equivalent steps are:"
msgstr ""

